A huge memory leak in the {{JiraImportProgressFilter}} we ship in OnDemand. Basically: 

{code}
public class JiraImportProgressFilter extends AbstractHttpFilter
{    
    private ImportResultStore importResultStore;
    
    @Override
    public void init(FilterConfig filterConfig) throws ServletException
    {
        super.init(filterConfig);
        servletContext = filterConfig.getServletContext();
        importResultStore = ComponentManager.getComponent(ImportResultStore.class);
    }
{code}

When JIRA does a restore, we actually destroy and re-create it again. In this code we are keeping  the {{importResultStore}} around from the first JIRA startup because the Filter is only created once. Through this reference we are keeping reference to a whole bunch objects and subsequently classes that should be destoryed. Even worse, during the import we are trying to use the ImportResultStore from JIRA's first startup which may not even work.

To work around this problem, we need to get the ComponentManager.getComponent(ImportResultStore.class) each time in the doFilter method. We need to be extra careful because calling ComponentManager methods while the restore is being run can cause deadlocks.

I wrote a plugin for Jira OnDemand (Svn plugin for Jira).
It is using the atlassian-connect.json
Yesterday I received a notification for a new customer through the 
{code}
"lifecycle": {
        "installed":
{code}
control, I got the following string:
{code}
clientKey   : jira:3014de0e-xxxx
baseUrl     : https://xxxx.atlassian.net
sharedSecret: xxx-xxx-xxx-xxx
description : Atlassian JIRA at null
{code}
The last part is obviously wrong. 
 I went back to my logs and sometime it also says {code}Atlassian JIRA at https://xxx.atlassian.net{code} but very often it says {code}at null{code}

